            "description": "\" BepiColombo is Europe's first mission to Mercury. It will launch in July 2016 on a journey to the smallest and least explored terrestrial planet in our Solar System. Arriving at Mercury in January 2023, it will endure temperatures in excess of 350\u00b0C and gather data during a 1 year nominal mission. \n\nOne of the instruments part of the payload is MSASI.\n\nPronounced \u2018musashi', MSASI (Mercury Sodium Atmospheric Spectral Imager) is a spectrometer devoted to the measurement of a narrow sodium D2 emission line (589nm \u00b1 0.028nm) against the bright surface of Mercury. A single high-resolution Fabry\u2013Perot etalon is used in combination with an ultra-narrow band-pass filter. Full-disk images of the planet are obtained by means of a single-axis scanning mirror in combination with the spin.\"\n\nMy contribution to this project was designing the mounts of a set of lenses that are part of the MSASI instrument, both the 3D and the 2D drawings (built to print).\n\n\n",
            "contributors": [
